e used to motivate patients undergoing treatment for such physical or psychological issues as diabetes management, smoking cessation, post-traumatic stress, obsessive-compulsive disorder, and depression.The first part of the book provides historical background to self-determination theory, showing that it is humanistically oriented and has three decades of empirical research behind it. In the process, the authors discuss why humanistic psychology fell out of favor in academic psychology; why "self-help" and New Age books have such perennial popularity; and why it is so important for authorities to support patients' sense of self. The remainder of the book presents many specific case examples to describe the theory's application.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAutonomie (Psychologie). 0aAutonomy (Psychology) 0aAutonomy (Psychology). 0aClinical health psychology. 0aHabitudes sanitaires. 0aHealth behavior. 0aPsychotherapy. 0aPsychothérapie. 0aSantéxPsychologie clinique. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Applied Psychology.2bisacsh1 aJoiner, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWilliams, Geoffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300128666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300128666.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles